{"id":14882018,"mediaExerciseId":"e9510700-6313-4133-9615-8ade506c75a6","exerciseName":"8","chapterName":"27","chapterTitle":"Leasing","groupId":612532,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":909,"solutions":[{"id":6504162,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"The goal of the assignment is to explain some reasons why a company might sell an asset and then lease it.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"First, let's explain this scenario: Companies can sell their assets to another entity and then create a lease agreement to continue to use the asset. This allows you to receive an immediate cash inflow and then, depending on the type of lease, you could buy back the asset.\n\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"But ***what would motivate a company to sell an asset and then lease it back?***\n\n- It may be that the company needs an inflow of cash to meet immediate needs, and the sale of the asset provides this cash inflow. Leasing, on the other hand, allows the use of the asset by the company.\n\n- Also, the company seeks to benefit from the tax advantages that a lease can offer, by negotiating a lease in which the new owner of the asset (the \nlessor) is responsible for assuming depreciation and taxes for owning the asset. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"2bd2a004-7d6f-45ae-99d5-373588c5cf74","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h"